<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-06-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-06-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="384" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d384">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113/1041</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-06-21"><hi rend="italic">June 21,
                                1927</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 559</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your despatch
                            No. 983 of April 6, 1927, with regard to a monopoly for the sale of
                            sulphur, saltpetre and other chemicals which has been established by the
                            Chinese authorities at Canton.</p>
                        <p>The Department is of the opinion that no further action need be taken in
                            this matter for the present.</p>
                        <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Joseph
                                    C. Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>